## II. ANOMALOUS CONTRAST THEORY — How to Decode It

**Core principle:** Every geological feature manifests as contrast in ≥2 independent physical properties. **No single-curve anomaly is sufficient.**

### Step 1: Establish background (shale baseline)
```javascript
// From the top 30% of log (high GR = shale), compute median:
RHOB_shale_bg = median(RHOB[0 : n*0.3])   // ~2.30-2.50 g/cc
NPHI_shale_bg = median(NPHI[0 : n*0.3])   // ~0.30-0.45 v/v
RT_bg = median(RT[0 : n*0.3])              // ~3-10 ohm-m (formation water)
```

### Step 2: Anomalous contrast = deviation from background
```javascript
κRHOB = (RHOB[i] - RHOB_shale_bg) / stdDev(RHOB)
κNPHI = (NPHI[i] - NPHI_shale_bg) / stdDev(NPHI)
κRT  = log10(RT[i]/RT_bg)                   // resistivity elevation
κGR  = (GR[i] - GR_shale) / stdDev(GR)      // GR anomaly

A = 0.2*κGR + 0.3*κRHOB + 0.3*κNPHI + 0.2*κRT  // composite
```

| A | Interpretation |
|---|----------------|
| > 1.5 | **STRONG** — proceed to quantitative interpretation |
| 0.5–1.5 | **MODERATE** — cross-plot confirmation required |
| < 0.5 | **WEAK** — W³ consensus before committing |

### Step 3: Fluid type from anomalous contrast pattern

| Pattern | Fluid | Mechanism |
|---------|-------|-----------|
| NPHI > PHIE_density + 0.05 AND RT elevation > 3× bg | **GAS** | Neutron porosity reads higher than density porosity (gas effect) |
| SW < 0.6 AND RT > 3× bg AND dRHOB > +0.05 | **OIL** | Resistivity high, density slightly elevated (hydrocarbon replaces water) |
| SW > 0.8 | **WATER** | Formation fully water-saturated |

### Step 4: Lithology from density-neutron cross-plot position

```
                    NPHI
                     ↑
         COAL       |
   SANDSTONE ←──────┼──→ DENSITY (RHOB)
                   ANHYDRITE
                   DOLOMITE
```

